    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_2804579925" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2804579925" />
    <a title="Quo" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/7392004-quo"><img alt="Quo" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1393910036p2/7392004.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2804579925?book_show_action=true">Apr 30, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Quo" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Quo" href="/user/show/7392004-quo">Quo</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9781400034215" href="/book/show/395183.The_Painted_Veil">review of another edition</a>

          <div><span class="uitext greyText">Recommends it for: </span>
           <span class="uitext reviewText">Anyone keen on the British Colonial experience or an exploration of Maughan's  skill as a novelist.</span></div>

          <div>
    <span class="greyText">Recommended to Quo by: </span>
      Local library book discussion selection
  </div>


          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/7392004-quo?shelf=british-lit">british-lit</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/7392004-quo?shelf=reviewed">reviewed</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2804579925" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer4099722002047006199">Early on in Somerset Maugham&apos;s novel, <i> The Painted Veil</i>, one of the more interesting but peripheral characters, a District Commissioner named Waddington, stationed up-country from British colonial Hong Kong at Mei-Tan Fu, an outpost plagued by cholera intones: &quot;I&apos;ve asked myself if you&apos;re both here to commit suicide?&quot; The couple in question are Walter Fane, M.D., a bacteriologist &amp; his wife Kitty and they have recently come from Hong Kong to this infected site because Walter has chosen it as a k</span>
  <span id="freeText4099722002047006199" style="display:none">Early on in Somerset Maugham's novel, <i> The Painted Veil</i>, one of the more interesting but peripheral characters, a District Commissioner named Waddington, stationed up-country from British colonial Hong Kong at Mei-Tan Fu, an outpost plagued by cholera intones: "I've asked myself if you're both here to commit suicide?" The couple in question are Walter Fane, M.D., a bacteriologist &amp; his wife Kitty and they have recently come from Hong Kong to this infected site because Walter has chosen it as a kind of exile, having recently discovered that Kitty has been having an affair with a fellow named Charlie Townsend, the sort of man the British used to label somewhat redundantly a "cad &amp; a bounder". <br><br>So continues a story that begins with the pair seeming to have little or nothing in common back in London &amp; having a conversation that demonstrates that they are almost uniquely incapable of communicating with each other, though Walter has declared himself to be deeply in love with Kitty, who is perplexed by his shy, halting declaration. However, after calling him an "odd creature", she then indicates that "his impassivity was vaguely impressive" &amp; though she has entertained other would-be suitors, no man has ever seemed so in love with her. <br><br><img src="https://i.gr-assets.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/hostedimages/1582682081i/29020272._SX540_.jpg" class="gr-hostedUserImg"><br><br>The early dialogue between them appears laughable, a display of the kind of alienation that normally takes years for a couple to achieve but Walter is soon to leave for Hong Kong and Kitty wishes to escape her family home where a younger sister has already long since married &amp; another is about to marry. Beyond that, she had nothing else on her calendar for the ensuing months, or so it seems. It might be seen as a caricature of a "very British marriage" in days past, particularly when women had few professional outlets &amp; the clock was ticking as it were.<br><br>After their impromptu marriage &amp; Walter's discovery of Kitty's intimate relationship with another man, the couple now face both isolation &amp; the threat of cholera + other disease at the outpost of Mei-Tan-Fu when Charlie Townsend refuses to leave his own wife and bond with Kitty in Hong Kong for fear of jeopardizing his career. While Kitty is deeply in love with Charley, she has misjudged her options &amp; must either return to England in disgrace or follow her husband into harm's way. <br><br>Having fled Hong Kong with his wife in tow, Dr. Fane loses himself in his work with the sick people in the village, while Kitty has little refuge or support, excepting the alcoholic D.C. named Waddington. Still, Walter &amp; Kitty do at times seem to make an effort at coming to terms with a relationship that has never really been subscribed to. For...<blockquote>Why could he not realize that beside all the terror of death under whose shadow they lay &amp; beside the awe of the beauty which she had only caught a glimpse of, their own affairs were trivial? What did it really matter that a silly woman had committed adultery &amp; why should her husband, face to face with the sublime, give it a thought? It was strange that Walter with all of his cleverness should have so little sense of proportion. <br><br>Because he had dressed a doll in gorgeous robes &amp; set her in a sanctuary to worship her &amp; then discovered that the doll was filled with sawdust, he could neither forgive himself nor her. His soul was lacerated. It was all make-believe that he had lived on, &amp; when the truth shattered it, he thought reality itself was shattered. He could not forgive her because he could not forgive himself.</blockquote>Meanwhile, Kitty "had nothing else to do &amp; after looking for so many days at the walled city across the water, she was not unwilling to have at least a glimpse of its mysterious streets." She discovers a French convent tending to orphans and serving as a dispensary for villagers afflicted with cholera. The nuns are in awe of her husband's tireless work with the sick &amp; some of that admiration transfers to Kitty, attempting to see Walter as others view him, at the same time also gradually becoming transfixed by the nuns' steadfast sense of devotion to God while so very far from their native French soil. Mother Superior tells Kitty that "one does not find peace in work or in a convent but only in one's soul." <br><br>The sensitive portrait of the nuns &amp; that of Kitty, bereft of love, in transition &amp; searching for meaning is really quite vivid &amp; captivating. Kitty is stunned by the suffering she sees, noticing a man whose life is "being throttled out of him in the dark clutch of the pestilence", with the beauty of nature contrasted with the seeming indifference of life when "men were writhing in agony &amp; going to their death in fear." However, Kitty begins to plug into life at the convent, offering her assistance with the orphans, feeling a sense of purpose, perhaps for the first time in her life, with the nuns...<blockquote>wonderful &amp; so kind and yet--I hardly know how to explain it--there is a wall between them &amp; me. It is as though they possessed a secret which made all the difference in their lives &amp; which I was unworthy to share. It is not faith; it is something deeper &amp; more significant: they walk in a different world from ours &amp; we shall always be strangers to them. Each day when the convent door closes behind me, I feel that for them I have ceased to exist.</blockquote>And yet, the nuns do care for Kitty &amp; are in her debt, just as they feel indebted for husband Walter's unswerving work as well. Beyond that, the celibate nuns quickly notice that Kitty is pregnant, something she seemed unaware of herself. Somerset Maughan seems to aptly describe Kitty's feelings &amp; in really memorable passages details her continuing search for meaning, with a focus on the spirituality of the nuns and also the "immemorial, dark &amp; inscrutable beliefs of the East", some quality or experience that when found "would make all the difference." This is a tale of transformation &amp; one either buys into it, as I did, or not. Some may find the tale melodramatic or unconvincing but I was charmed by the strength of Maugham's language, with passages such as...<blockquote>New ideas flitted about her heart like yellow butterflies in the sunshine &amp; she hoped to be so much better in the future; freedom like a spirit of light had beckoned her on &amp; the world was like a spacious plain through which she could walk light of foot with head erect.</blockquote>Without wishing to give away the reason to potential readers of the novel, Kitty decides to book passage on a P&amp;O steamship bound for London. At novel's end, I was uplifted by Kitty's reunion with her father, wherein Kitty, following disembarkation just after the death of her imperious mother, attempts to do with her seemingly detached father that which she was unable to do with her husband Walter. <br><br>Will Kitty's plan work out?? Yes I say, especially if I am permitted to add a sequel of my own devising. In any case, I turned the last page of Somerset Maugham's <i>The Painted Veil</i> with a great sense of optimism for Kitty &amp; her pending child, as well as joy that I had chanced to read this early (1925) novel by Maugham, even if I found <i>The Razor's Edge</i> somewhat more engaging!<br><br>For what it is worth, Somerset Maugham was bisexual (he was married &amp; had a daughter though mostly slanted towards men), bi-professional (having been trained as a medical doctor but making his living as a novelist &amp; playwright), bi-national (having been born in France but within the British embassy there) &amp; bilingual. Actually, since he studied at the University of Heidelberg, he was likely trilingual. <br><br>Maugham was not however ambidextrous but one wonders if his dualities somehow allowed the author to visualize countering points of view &amp; to create compelling characters very unlike himself, Kitty Fane for example. Maugham was an agnostic but seemed able to craft an engaging portrayal of what inspired the French Catholic nuns to dedicate their lives to helping the poor &amp; needy in China. <br><br>I believe that Dr. Fane's last words: <i>The dog it was that died</i>, from a 1766 Oliver Goldsmith poem, "An Elegy on the Death of a Mad Dog" provide some terminal insight (so to speak) into the author's view of Kitty's husband. <br><br><img src="https://i.gr-assets.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/hostedimages/1582682081i/29020273.jpg" class="gr-hostedUserImg"><br><br>*There are at least two film versions of <i>The Painted Veil</i>, including a 1934 movie with Greta Garbo as Kitty in an adaptation that takes great liberties with the Maugham novel.</span>
  <a data-text-id="4099722002047006199" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


