    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_1542670352" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1542670352" />
    <a title="Rebecca" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/5875398-rebecca"><img alt="Rebecca" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1599578317p2/5875398.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1542670352?book_show_action=true">May 29, 2018</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Rebecca" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Rebecca" href="/user/show/5875398-rebecca">Rebecca</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/5875398-rebecca?shelf=buddy-read">buddy-read</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/5875398-rebecca?shelf=obscure-classics">obscure-classics</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1542670352" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer15957605340301714296">I read this as a buddy read with my mother. This review is based on the reading notes I shared with her via e-mail. It was my third novel from Maugham; all have been excellent. Although he seems to have gone out of fashion, he was well respected in his time and at least a few of his books remain widely read. His titles are often taken from literary sources; here the title and epigraph are from a Shelley poem. Also, he explains in the preface that he got the idea for the plot from Dante’s <i>Purgato</i></span>
  <span id="freeText15957605340301714296" style="display:none">I read this as a buddy read with my mother. This review is based on the reading notes I shared with her via e-mail. It was my third novel from Maugham; all have been excellent. Although he seems to have gone out of fashion, he was well respected in his time and at least a few of his books remain widely read. His titles are often taken from literary sources; here the title and epigraph are from a Shelley poem. Also, he explains in the preface that he got the idea for the plot from Dante’s <i>Purgatorio</i> (and that he was forced to change the characters’ last name and make up a colony name to fill in for Hong Kong after threats of a libel suit). <a class="jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction">(view spoiler)</a><span class="spoilerContainer" style="display: none">[Walter’s last words are also a literary allusion: “The dog it was that died” comes from Oliver Goldsmith’s poem “An Elegy on the Death of a Mad Dog” (1766) – after a rabid dog bites a man, everyone thinks he will die. Instead, the dog dies. Walter is reflecting on the irony that he brought Kitty to this remote Chinese outpost so that she might die of cholera as punishment for her adultery, but he dies instead.<br /><br />It’s a sudden opening as Kitty and her lover, Charlie Townsend, are caught in the act. Stories of adulteresses were probably still fairly rare back in 1925. As in <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2114433802" rel="nofollow noopener"><i>Madame Bovary</i></a> and <i>Anna Karenina</i>, the heroine must be punished for what she’s done. Maugham writes of “the sad perspicacity that she had learned in suffering,” a line that could also be applied to Bathsheba Everdene in Thomas Hardy’s <i>Far from the Madding Crowd</i>. From now on Kitty will live a life of duty (to her father), but she vows to raise her daughter to live independently of men. <a class="jsHideSpoiler spoilerAction">(hide spoiler)</a>]</span><br /><br />Kitty’s mother, Mrs. Garstin, married for money and status and encouraged her daughter to do the same. Kitty knew within a few months that she’d made a mistake by marrying Walter, a microbiologist – “she was not quite at ease with him. He had no gaiety. … She had discovered very soon that he had an unhappy disability to lose himself. He was self-conscious.” <a class="jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction">(view spoiler)</a><span class="spoilerContainer" style="display: none">[By contrast, Charlie “has the gift of making every one he meets feel that he is the one person in the world he wants to see.” We get an outsider’s view of Charlie through Waddington, and despite that described charisma Kitty’s view of her lover starts to change. <a class="jsHideSpoiler spoilerAction">(hide spoiler)</a>]</span><br /><br />Maugham had a deep understanding of human psychology, male and female, and wrote magnificently about the search for purpose in a life ruled by fate. I loved the philosophical discussions between Kitty and Waddington about what matters and how to live well. Kitty says, “I’m looking for something and I don’t quite know what it is.” Waddington replies, “Some of us look for the Way in opium and some in God, some of us in whiskey and some in love.” Later he says, “I have an idea that the only thing which makes it possible to regard this world we live in without disgust is the beauty which now and then men create out of the chaos. The pictures they paint, the music they compose, the books they write, and the lives they lead. Of all these the richest in beauty is the beautiful life. That is the perfect work of art.”</span>
  <a data-text-id="15957605340301714296" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


